Comment_contributor: From three onwards the Plural termination ga may be used
It may be observed that the digits of the second hand correspond, to some extent, to those of the first
ro in pogo-ro is do in a more common form
a appears as ‘one’ in a tale
pa is always ‘one,’ except a the beginning of a series. ... The unit above ten is nipiti; and tale, ten, is not needed; pa nipiti one the unit above ten
edo is two and ten is not named
edoga is used as well as edo nipiti
edo is two and ten is not named

the presence of a name for the unit above twenty, lisoa, different from that above ten, nipiti, is a mark in Savo that counting by twenties, nebolo, is an ancient practice ... The name for twenty is distinct, as in Bugotu
the unit above nebolo is lisoa; nebolo lisoa pa a score the unit above one
Some, however, only use lisoa for the sum above a hundred, and simply add the unit after the score
As in Gao, another designation comes in for the tens above the score, liza; ... three sets of ten
some use tale or sale all through
some use tale or sale all through
The sum above a hundred is lisoa.
The word for a thousand is probably borrowed.
